node.text:
Saturn, imaged by @nightskyflying
.
Quote "This here is a shot from a few nights back using just a single run of data, but it was some pretty solid data allowing me to pull out a lot of detail. I boosted the colors a bit unnaturally to bring out the definition in the hexagon at the north pole. The starfield in the background is from a separate shot and then blended together during processing."

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Earth 🌏 Space 🌕 Galaxy 🌌 on September 14, 2021. May be an image of planet and text.

node.text:
Did you know? All of the giant planets in our solar system have rings around them. Saturn might be the planet that we associate with rings, but Jupiter, Uranus, and Neptune also have pretty sizable rings too. Astronomers learned about Jupiter’s rings back in the early 1600s, and since then it has been studied thoroughly. Jupiter's rings are very faint and made of dust and small pieces of rocks, not ice!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
In 1979, the Voyager 1 and Voyager 2 spacecraft discovered rings near Jupiter. They consist of very small dust grains (0.2-200 microns). These dust particles gradually fall into the atmosphere of Jupiter, and their place is taken by others that are formed when small satellites, especially Amalthea (Jupiter's moon), collide with meteorite bodies.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Earth 🌏 Space 🌕 Galaxy 🌌 on September 13, 2021.

node.text:
This is Messier 57, a beautiful example of a planetary nebula, the glowing remains of a sun-like star! The tiny white dot that’s found at the centre of this nebula is actually a white dwarf star, the leftover core of a star that has shed its out shells of gas out into space. Found in the constellation of Lyra about 2,000 light-years away.

Credit: @daviddayag

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Earth 🌏 Space 🌕 Galaxy 🌌 on September 12, 2021. May be an image of sky and nature.

node.text:
Moon Corona, Halo and Arcs over Manitoba, Canada
Image Credit: @brentmckean (Brent McKean)

The colorful rings are a corona caused by quantum diffraction by small drops of water or ice near the direction of the Moon. Outside of that, a 22-degree halo was created by moonlight refracting through six-sided cylindrical ice crystals. To the sides are moon dogs, caused by light refracting through thin, flat, six-sided ice platelets as they flittered toward the ground. Visible at the top and bottom of the 22-degree halo are upper and lower tangent arcs, created by moonlight refracting through nearly horizontal hexagonal ice cylinders.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Earth 🌏 Space 🌕 Galaxy 🌌 on September 11, 2021. May be an image of ocean, cloud and nature.

node.text:
A spectacular Mammatus clouds formation in a sunset sky over New Mexico 😍

These distinct bulges or pouches are formed by cold air sinking down to form the pockets contrary to the puffs of clouds rising through the convection of warm air. Mammatus clouds often form in association with Cumulonimbus clouds, which usually indicate severe thunderstorms due to their huge mass of unstable air. This could also mean that there is a chance of hail, heavy rain and lightning in the vicinity.

Capture date: May 2012

📷 Brad Hannon - Photography @bradhannon
